  "prompt": "What were the terms to the Treaty of Versailles?",
  "response": "The Treaty of Versailles, signed on June 28, 1919, officially ended World War I. Some of the main terms included:\n\n1. **Territorial Losses**:\n   - **Alsace-Lorraine** was returned to France.\n   - **Eupen and Malmedy** were given to Belgium.\n   - **Northern Schleswig** was ceded to Denmark.\n   - The Saar Basin was placed under the administration of the League of Nations, with its coal mines assigned to France for 15 years.\n   - **Danzig** (now Gda\u0144sk) was declared a free city.\n   - The **Rhineland** was to be demilitarized.\n   - **West Prussia, Posen, and parts of Upper Silesia** were given to Poland.\n   - **Memel** was given to Lithuania.\n\n2. **Colonial Losses**: Germany's overseas colonies were taken and administered by the League of Nations under the mandates system.\n\n3. **Military Restrictions**:\n   - The German army was limited to 100,000 troops.\n   - Conscription was abolished.\n   - Tanks, military aircraft, and submarines were prohibited.\n   - The Navy could only have six battleships and no submarines.\n   \n4. **War Guilt and Reparations**:\n   - Article 231, the \"war guilt clause,\" placed full responsibility for the war on Germany and its allies.\n   - Germany was required to pay reparations, initially set at 132 billion gold marks (around $33 billion at the time).\n\n5. **Economic Restrictions**:\n   - Germany was forbidden from merging with Austria (Anschluss).\n   - Trade agreements and economic controls were imposed.\n\n6. **League of Nations**:\n   - Establishment of the League of Nations, with Germany initially excluded.\n\nThe Treaty of Versailles was intended to prevent Germany from becoming a military threat again, but it caused significant resentment in Germany, leading to severe economic problems and political instability.",
